hands_on_practices.problem:
Let the first-order (FO) language be $L=\{\lt\}$ with a single binary relation symbol. Let $M=(\mathbb{Q},\lt)$ be the structure of the rational numbers with the usual strict order, and let $T=\operatorname{Th}(M)$ be the complete $L$-theory of dense linear orders without endpoints. Using only core definitions such as elementary embedding and prime model, determine whether $M$ is prime for $T$ by verifying the existence, for every $N\models T$, of an elementary embedding $f:M\to N$. Encode your conclusion by the indicator
$$
\chi(M,T)=\begin{cases}
1 & \text{if $M$ is prime for $T$},\\
0 & \text{otherwise.}
\end{cases}
$$
Provide the value of $\chi(M,T)$ as a single number. No rounding is required, and no units apply.
